        <paragraphs>
            <title>Quotient to a Power Rule</title>
            <p>We have the <xref ref="exponent-rules-product-to-a-power" autoname="title" />, which applies the outer exponent to each factor in the product inside the parentheses.  What happens if we apply an exponent to a quotient instead?</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Let <m>y</m> be a real number, where <m>y \neq 0</m>. Simplify <m>\left( \dfrac{7}{y} \right)^4</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Writing the expression without an exponent and then simplifying, we have:<md>
                    <mrow>\left( \frac{7}{y} \right)^4 \amp= \left( \frac{7}{y} \right) \left( \frac{7}{y} \right) \left( \frac{7}{y} \right) \left( \frac{7}{y} \right)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{7 \cdot 7 \cdot 7 \cdot 7}{y \cdot y \cdot y \cdot y}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{7^4}{y^4}</mrow>
                </md>Similar to the product to a power rule, we essentially applied the outer exponent to the entire numerator and denominator. </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>The previous example shows how the <term>Quotient to a Power Rule</term> works. For real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, with <m>b \neq 0</m>:<me>\left( \frac{a}{b}  \right)^{n} = \frac{a^{n}}{b^{n}}</me>When you have a quotient raised to an exponent, you apply the exponent to the entire numerator and denominator.</p>

