                    <cell halign="center"><m>\mathord{?}</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\mathord{?}</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>We can see that <q>removing a factor of <m>2</m></q> really means that we're dividing the value by <m>2</m>. Following that pattern, we can see that moving from <m>2^1</m> to <m>2^0</m> means that we need to divide the value <m>2</m> by <m>2</m>.  <m>2\div 2 = 1</m>, so we have: <me>2^0 = 1</me></p>


        <p>Another way to structure our table would be to use the fact that multiplication by <m>1</m> has no effect on any number's value.  We could rewrite the second column of the table like so:</p>

        <table>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell halign="right">power</cell>
                    <cell> </cell>
                    <cell halign="center">product</cell>
                    <cell> </cell>
                    <cell>value</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell halign="right"><m>2^4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell halign="center"><m>1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>16</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell halign="right"><m>2^3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell halign="center"><m>1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell halign="right"><m>2^2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell halign="center"><m>1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell halign="right"><m>2^1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell halign="center"><m>1 \cdot 2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell halign="right"><m>2^0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell halign="center"><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>Now the numerical meaning of <q>no factors of 2</q> is more clear. <q>No factors of 2</q> have the same effect as multiplying by <m>1</m>. Mathematically, we can read the expression <m>2^0</m> as <q>zero factors of 2.</q> Multiplying by zero factors of any non-zero real number has the same effect as not having multiplied by anything at all.  That's the effect as having multiplied by <m>1</m>.</p>

        <p>This gives us our <term>Zero Exponent Rule</term>: for any real number <m>a</m>, where <m>a \neq 0</m> <me>a^0 = 1</me></p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify <m>\dfrac{x^8}{\left(x^2\right)^4}</m>, assuming <m>x \neq 0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We'll first focus on the parentheses and exponent in the denominator, using the <xref ref="exponent-rules-power-to-a-power" autoname="title" />.  Then we'll finish using the <xref ref="exponent-rules-quotient" autoname="title" />.<md>
                    <mrow> \frac{x^8}{\left(x^2\right)^4} \amp= \frac{x^8}{x^{2\cdot 4}} </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= \frac{x^8}{x^8} </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= x^{8-8} </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= x^0 </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= 1 </mrow>
                </md>While this one started out being fairly similar to previous examples, when we arrived at the line <m>\dfrac{x^8}{x^8}</m> and carried out the division, all of the factors of <m>x</m> canceled from the numerator and denominator.  We were left with <m>x^0</m>, which we now know equals <m>1</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the following expressions, assuming <m>x \neq 0</m> and <m>y \neq 0</m>.
                <ol>
                    <li><p><m>3x^0</m></p></li>   
                    <li><p><m>-8^0</m></p></li>   
                    <li><p><m>(-8)^0</m></p></li>   
                    <li><p><m>(173 x^4 y^{251})^0</m></p></li>   
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To simplify any of these expressions, it is critical that we remember an exponent only applies to what it is touching or immediately next to.<ol>
                <li><p>In the expresssion <m>3x^0</m>, the exponent <m>0</m> only applies to the <m>x</m>:<md>
                    <mrow> 3x^0 \amp= 3\cdot x^0  </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= 3\cdot 1 </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= 3 </mrow>
                </md>Since the exponent did not apply to the <m>3</m>, the <m>3</m> stayed a <m>3</m>. </p></li>   
                <li><p>In the expresssion <m>-8^0</m>, the exponent only applies to the <m>8</m>.  We should remember that <m>-8^0 = -1 \cdot 8^0</m>:<md>
                    <mrow> -8^0  \amp=  -1\cdot 8^0 </mrow>
                    <mrow>   \amp=  -1\cdot 1 </mrow>
                    <mrow>   \amp=  -1 </mrow>
                </md></p></li>   
                <li><p>In contrast to the previous example, the exponent in <m>(-8)^0</m> applies to everything inside the parentheses, <m>-8</m>.<md>
                    <mrow> (-8)^0  \amp=  1 </mrow>
                </md></p></li>   
                <li><p>In the expresssion <m>(173x^4y^251)^0</m>, the exponent <m>0</m> applies to everything inside the parentheses.<md>
                    <mrow>  (173 x^4 y^{251})^0 \amp=  1 </mrow>
                </md></p></li>   
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Now that we have exponent rules for products, quotients, and a rule for an exponent of zero, let's collect them together.</p>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Exponent Rules</title>

        <list xml:id="list-exponent-rules">
            <title>Summary of the Rules of Exponents for Multiplication and Division</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are real numbers, and <m>n</m> and <m>m</m> are positive integers, then we have the following rules:</p>
            </introduction>
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="exponent-rules-product">
                    <title>Product Rule</title>
                    <p><m>a^{n} \cdot a^{m} = a^{n+m}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exponent-rules-power-to-a-power">
                    <title>Power to a Power Rule</title>
                    <p><m>(a^{n})^{m} = a^{n\cdot m}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exponent-rules-product-to-a-power">
                    <title>Product to a Power Rule</title>
                    <p><m>(ab)^{n} = a^{n} \cdot b^{n}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exponent-rules-quotient">
                    <title>Quotient Rule</title>
                    <p><m>\dfrac{a^{n}}{a^{m}} = a^{n-m}</m>, as long as <m>a \neq 0</m></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exponent-rules-quotient-to-a-power">
                    <title>Quotient to a Power Rule</title>
                    <p><m>\left( \dfrac{a}{b}  \right)^{n} = \dfrac{a^{n}}{b^{n}}</m>, as long as <m>b \neq 0</m></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="exponent-rules-zero-exponent">
                    <title>Zero Exponent Rule</title>
                    <p><m>a^{0} = 1</m>, as long as <m>a \neq 0</m></p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <conclusion>

                <p>Remember that you should understand why all of these rules make sense. When in doubt, carefully rewrite powers as products to see which rule makes sense.</p>
            </conclusion>
        </list>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Why we have <q><m>a \neq 0</m></q> and <q><m>b \neq 0</m></q> for some rules</title>

            <p>Whenever we're working with division, we have to be careful to make sure the rules we state don't ever imply that we might be dividing by zero.  Dividing by zero leads us to expressions that either have no meaning or their value is unable to be determined.  <m>\dfrac{9}{0}</m> is undefined and <m>\dfrac{0}{0}</m> is indeterminate.</p>

            <p>This explains why we need to include such restrictions for the <xref ref="exponent-rules-quotient" autoname="title" /> or the <xref ref="exponent-rules-quotient-to-a-power" autoname="title" />: We must avoid possibly suggesting a denominator might be zero.  This doesn't address why we need this restriction on the <xref ref="exponent-rules-zero-exponent" autoname="title" />.</p>

            <p>The expression <m>0^0</m> is called indeterminate.  If you try to determine the value of <m>0^0</m> using the logic of <m>a^0=1</m>, you might be inclined to conclude <m>0^0=1</m>.  On the other hand, if you look back to the value of <m>0^n</m> for any natural number n, you'd conclude that <m>0^0=0</m>.  Since there is no consistent answer, we simply say that we cannot determine this expression's value.  The value is indeterminant.</p>
            
        </paragraphs>


