    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Sums and Powers? No Rules!</title>

        <p>Have you noticed that all of the exponent rules focus on multiplication and division?  None of them involve addition or subtraction in the initial expression.</p>

        <example>
            <p>Simplify <m>(1+2)^4</m>.</p>

            <p>We have two possible approaches: following the order of operations or trying to use an exponent rule.</p>

            <p>If we follow the order of operations, we have <md>
                <mrow>(1+2)^4 \amp= (3)^4</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= 81</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>If we try to use an exponent rule, the natural one people try to use is the <xref ref="exponent-rules-product-to-a-power" autoname="title" /> and the work would probably look like <md>
                <mrow>(1+2)^4 \amp= 1^4 + 2^4</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= 1 + 16</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= 17</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>Clearly we do not obtain the same result using the two different methods.  Why didn't the second method work?</p>
        </example>

        <p>The reason why none of the rules work for addition or subtraction comes down to what an exponent means: whole number exponents are short hand for repeated multiplication, not repeated addition or subtraction.  Trying to apply multiplication rules in situations that do not use multiplication simply doesn't work.</p>

        <p>Trying to replace the <xref ref="exponent-rules-product" autoname="title" /> with an equivalent <q>sum rule,</q> say <m>a^n + a^m = a^{n+m}</m>, will also fail. <md>
            <mrow>a^n + a^m \amp\stackrel{?}{=} a^{n+m}</mrow>
            <mrow>2^3 + 2^4 \amp\stackrel{?}{=} 2^{3+4}</mrow>
            <mrow>24 \amp\neq 128</mrow>
        </md> Yikes, that's not even close. This attempt at a <q>sum rule</q> falls apart with our first attempt. In fact, without knowing values for <m>a</m>, <m>n</m>, and <m>m</m>, there's no way to simplify the expression <m>a^n + a^m</m>. </p>

